Q2. Navigate to http://MACHINE_IP/ in your browser and click on the "Reflected XSS" tab on the navbar; craft a reflected XSS payload that will cause a popup saying "Hello".
 [HINT]: Add the following payload in the comment section: 
      ''' 
         <script>alert(“Hello”)</script>
      '''
Ans: ThereIsMoreToXSSThanYouThink

Q3. On the same reflective page, craft a reflected XSS payload that will cause a popup with your machines IP address.
  [HINT]: Add the following Payload:
      '''
         <script>alert(window.location.hostname)</script>
      '''
Ans: ReflectiveXss4TheWin

Q4. Now navigate to http://MACHINE_IP/ in your browser and click on the "Stored XSS" tab on the navbar; make an account.
    Then add a comment and see if you can insert some of your own HTML.
  [HINT]: Add any HTML code in the comment section.You can find any html syntax from google.

Ans: HTML_T4gs

Q5. On the same page, create an alert popup box appear on the page with your document cookies.
[HINT]: Use the following payload:
     '''    
       <script>alert(document.cookies)</script>
     '''
Ans: W3LL_D0N3_LVL2s

Q6. Change “XSS Playground” to “I am a hacker” by adding a comment and using Javascript.
  [HINT]: Using the hint provided, use this js code 
      '''
        <script>document.querySelector(‘#thm-title’).textContent = ‘I am a hacker’</script>
      '''
Ans: websites_can_be_easily_defaced_with_xss

